&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot; style=&quot; text-align: left; direction: ltr; unicode-bidi: embed;&quot;&gt;Nur al-Din Jami&#8217;s &#8220;Gift to the Noble.&#8221; Jami (d. 1492), the last of the classical Persian poets, was a mystic linked to the Sufi Naqshbandi order in Herat (in modern Afghanistan). One of his most famous poems, &#8220;Gift to the Noble (or Gift of the Freemen),&#8221; is a collection of aphorisms and moral parables in rhymed poetic stanzas. &amp;#160;Jami presented this collection to the leader of the Naqshbandis, who was also known as &#8220;Lord of the Nobles/Freemen.&#8221; This manuscript was copied in 1484, just three years after Jami composed the poem. Yahuda Ms.Ar.1013&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;

