&lt;body&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot; style=&quot; text-align: left; direction: ltr; unicode-bidi: embed;&quot;&gt;&lt;span&gt;S.H. Bergmann was a philosopher and intellectual. Bergmann and Kafka grew up together in Prague. Although they attended the same schools and were close friends, Bergmann was an avid Zionist and his Jewish origins were central to his self- identity. He immigrated to Palestine in 1920, and was appointed as Head of the National Library, an office he held until 1935. Bergmann was appointed also as Professor of Philosophy at the Hebrew University and served as the University Rector. Together with &lt;span style=&quot; color: red;&quot;&gt;Martin Buber, Gershom Scholem, &lt;/span&gt;and others,&lt;b&gt; &lt;/b&gt;Bergmann was a member of &lt;i&gt;Brit Shalom&lt;/i&gt;, &quot;Covenant of Peace&quot;, which supported the Coexistence of Jews and Arabs in one state.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The Scroll seen here was donated to the NLI by the Adini-Edel family.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Unlike the Torah scrolls usually used in Synagogues, this is a miniature scroll,&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;written in micrographic script.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It was either written or owned by a well-known Jewish scholar from eastern&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Europe by the name of Rabbai Judah Edel (1757 &#8211; 1828), who in his capacity as a&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;preacher travelled much and needed a compact version of the Torah to take with&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;him. After it was donated to the library it turned out that one of the library&apos;s most&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;experienced manuscript experts was a descendent of Rabbai Edel.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;!DOCTYPE html PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD XHTML 1.0 Transitional//EN&quot; &quot;http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml1/DTD/xhtml1-transitional.dtd&quot;&gt;&lt;html xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml&quot;&gt;
