&lt;body&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot; style=&quot; margin-left: -7.1pt;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size: 12.0pt; font-family: Arial,sans-serif; color: black; background: white;&quot;&gt;Menahem de Lonzano did not note at the end of his manuscript, as authors often did, neither the place nor the time in which he wrote it. Yet in one place he noted that &quot;the exile has lasted 370 years after the sixth millennium&#8230;Menahem D&quot;L&quot;. This meant that the manuscript was copied &amp;#160;370 years after the creation, which is the year 1610 CE, exactly 400 years before it was rediscovered!&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot; style=&quot; margin-left: -7.1pt;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size: 12.0pt; font-family: Arial,sans-serif; color: black; background: white;&quot;&gt;As for the place, it is most probable that it was copied in Egypt, as De Lonzano mentions negotiations with a one of the great scholars living in Egypt at that time.&amp;#160;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;

&lt;!DOCTYPE html PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD XHTML 1.0 Transitional//EN&quot; &quot;http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml1/DTD/xhtml1-transitional.dtd&quot;&gt;&lt;html xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml&quot;&gt;
