&lt;body&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot; style=&quot; margin-left: -7.1pt;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size: 12.0pt; font-family: Arial,sans-serif; color: black; background: white;&quot;&gt;De Lonzano&apos;s manuscript contains &quot;Derushim&quot; or&amp;#160; lessons which he recorded from the writings of two famous Kabbalists from Safed, R. Hayyim Vital and R. Joseph b. Tabul, who passed on the mystical teachings of their teacher, the famous Rabbi Isaac Luria also known as &lt;i&gt;The Ari&lt;/i&gt;. The book, 200 pages long, is full of De Lonzano&apos;s often quite critical comments. One of the newly discovered lessons, which is especially important, is Luria&apos;s &lt;i&gt;Lesson on the Primordial Man&lt;/i&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size: 12.0pt; font-family: Arial,sans-serif; color: black; background: white;&quot;&gt;as passed on by Rabbi Hayyim Vital.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;

&lt;!DOCTYPE html PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD XHTML 1.0 Transitional//EN&quot; &quot;http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml1/DTD/xhtml1-transitional.dtd&quot;&gt; 
