&lt;body&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot; style=&quot; margin-left: -7.1pt;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size: 12.0pt; font-family: Arial,sans-serif; color: black; background: white;&quot;&gt;The book of the &lt;i&gt;Zohar&lt;/i&gt;, the central opus of the Kabbalah, was composed by Rabbi Moshe de Leon in Guadalajara between 1280 - 1286, but is believed by some scholars to have been written by a circle of authors.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot; style=&quot; margin-left: -7.1pt;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size: 12.0pt; font-family: Arial,sans-serif; color: black; background: white;&quot;&gt;The book purports to have been written by Rabbi Shimeon Bar Yohai, a Jewish sage of the second century, who while hiding from the Roman persecutions in a cave for thirteen years studied the Torah, inspired by the prophet.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot; style=&quot; margin-left: -7.1pt; text-autospace: none;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size: 12.0pt; font-family: Arial,sans-serif; color: black; background: white;&quot;&gt;The &lt;i&gt;Zohar&lt;/i&gt; is a mystical commentary on the &lt;/span&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size: 12.0pt; font-family: Arial,sans-serif; color: red; background: white;&quot;&gt;Torah&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size: 12.0pt; font-family: Arial,sans-serif; color: red; background: white;&quot;&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size: 12.0pt; font-family: Arial,sans-serif; color: black; background: white;&quot;&gt;(Pentateuch).&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot; style=&quot; margin-left: -7.1pt; text-autospace: none;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size: 12.0pt; font-family: Arial,sans-serif;&quot;&gt;It revolves round two axes: one - the mysteries of the emanations of God, called the &lt;/span&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size: 12.0pt; font-family: Arial,sans-serif;&quot;&gt;Sefirot, &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size: 12.0pt; font-family: Arial,sans-serif;&quot;&gt;which are reflected in many symbols in the created world; the other - the situation of the Jew and his fate in this world and in the world of souls. The &lt;i&gt;Zohar&lt;/i&gt;&apos;s major interest was a creation of an alternative reality where redemption replaces exile. Human action is thus seen as a vital contribution in the cosmic struggle between exile and redemption.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;

&lt;!DOCTYPE html PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD XHTML 1.0 Transitional//EN&quot; &quot;http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml1/DTD/xhtml1-transitional.dtd&quot;&gt; 
