}
p {
margin-top: 0pt;  margin-bottom: 0pt;
}
--&gt;
&lt;/style&gt;
&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;body&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Elimelech Basch&apos;s eldest daughter, Bluma (Perhiya), was the only one of the Basch family who survived. &amp;#160;Bluma emigrated to Israel, changed her name to Perhiya and built a new family. &amp;#160;Perhiya has three children, many grandchildren and a newborn great granddaughter. &amp;#160;She is now 87 years old. She is still an active volounteer in her hometown Lydda (Lod). &amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Photograph: In the center Perhiya receiving a token of gratitude from the city of Lydda for her long years as a volunteer.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Photograph: Perhiya&apos;s testimony, given in January 1956, regarding the murder of her family. &amp;#160;The testimony was given to the Yad Vashem museum for the memory of the Holocaust in Jerusalem, Israel.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;

&lt;!DOCTYPE html PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD XHTML 1.0 Transitional//EN&quot; &quot;http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml1/DTD/xhtml1-transitional.dtd&quot;&gt;&lt;html xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml&quot;&gt;
&lt;head&gt;
&lt;meta name=&quot;generator&quot; content=&quot;EditLive! 7.6.2.10&quot; /&gt;
