margin: 0cm;  margin-bottom: .0001pt;  font-size: 11.0pt;  font-family: Calibri, sans-serif;
}
--&gt;
&lt;/style&gt;
&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;body&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot; style=&quot; margin-left: -7.1pt;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size: 12.0pt; font-family: Arial,sans-serif; color: black; background: white;&quot;&gt;The &lt;i&gt;Kabbalah&lt;/i&gt; in general, and especially the &lt;i&gt;Zohar&lt;/i&gt;, was considered by many a doctrine which can be correctly understood only by scholars who are well versed in the Jewish sources. After Sabbateanism, Kabbalah&apos;s delving into basic questions regarding the nature of the divine caused it to be conceived as a dangerous doctrine which may lead simple believers astray. It was thus usually forbidden to people below the age of forty and to those who were not learned.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot; style=&quot; margin-left: -7.1pt;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size: 12.0pt; font-family: Arial,sans-serif; color: black; background: white;&quot;&gt;The expansion of Kabbalah was much assisted by the invention of print, overcoming the restrictions which had been imposed on its dissemination and study.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;

&lt;!DOCTYPE html PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD XHTML 1.0 Transitional//EN&quot; &quot;http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml1/DTD/xhtml1-transitional.dtd&quot;&gt; 
&lt;html xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml&quot;&gt;
&lt;head&gt;
&lt;meta name=&quot;generator&quot; content=&quot;EditLive! 7.6.2.10&quot; /&gt;
