&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot; style=&quot; margin-top: 0cm; margin-right: -17.05pt; margin-bottom: .0001pt; margin-left: -7.1pt; line-height: 115%; text-autospace: none;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: Arial,sans-serif; background: white;&quot;&gt;Later on Safed Kabbalah &lt;span style=&quot; color: black;&quot;&gt;spread to Egypt, Turkey and Italy, and then to Jewish centers all over the Jewish Diaspora.&amp;#160;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot; style=&quot; margin-top: 0cm; margin-right: -17.05pt; margin-bottom: .0001pt; margin-left: -7.1pt; line-height: 115%; text-autospace: none;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: Arial,sans-serif; color: black; background: white;&quot;&gt;In the 17th and 18th centuries Safed Kabbalah and &lt;i&gt;Sefer ha-Zohar&lt;/i&gt; generated the messianic movement known as Sabbateanism. In Eastern Europe it stimulated a special movement called the&amp;#160;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: Arial,sans-serif;&quot;&gt;Hasidut&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: Arial,sans-serif; color: black; background: white;&quot;&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;

&lt;!DOCTYPE html PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD XHTML 1.0 Transitional//EN&quot; &quot;http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml1/DTD/xhtml1-transitional.dtd&quot;&gt;&lt;html xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml&quot;&gt;
