&lt;p class=&quot;MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst&quot; style=&quot; margin-left: 70.9pt; text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-family: Arial,sans-serif;&quot;&gt;In 1629, W.J. Blaeu printed a new world atlas containing 45 maps. One of these was a map of the Holy Land as seen by Moses from Mt. Nevo just before his death and after forty years of wandering with the Israelites in the desert.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;MsoListParagraphCxSpLast&quot; style=&quot; margin-left: 70.9pt; text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-family: Arial,sans-serif;&quot;&gt;The cartouche on the bottom right is surrounded by the figures of Moses and Aaron. In this image, Moses had just descended from Mt. Sinai with the Tablets and is shown according to Jerome&apos;s mistaken translation of Exodus 34:29, with horns over his head. Next to him stands Aaron, the High Priest, in his special attire and paraphernalia.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
